Looks like it is compiled to static consumer:
boolean sameObject = false;
Consumer<JanusGraphVertexProperty> c1 = null;
for (int i = 0; i < 2; i++) {
    Consumer<JanusGraphVertexProperty> c2 = new Consumer<JanusGraphVertexProperty>() {
        @Override
        public void accept(JanusGraphVertexProperty p) {
            p.remove();
        }
    };
    if (c1 == null) c1 = c2;
    else sameObject = c1 == c2; // false
}
when using method reference or lambda function, result is different:
boolean sameObject = false;
Consumer<JanusGraphVertexProperty> c1 = null;
for (int i = 0; i < 2; i++) {
    Consumer<JanusGraphVertexProperty> c2 = JanusGraphElement::remove;
    if (c1 == null) c1 = c2;
    else sameObject = c1 == c2; // true
}
Example modified from https://stackoverflow.com/questions/23983832/is-method-reference-caching-a-good-idea-in-java-8/23991339#23991339

